<subsection xml:id="subsec-Total-value-of-digits-in-decimals">
    <title>Total value of digits in decimals</title>
  
           <p>
            The total value of digits in a decimal is found by multiplying each digit by its place value and summing the results.
        </p>
        <p>
             The place value decreases in powers of 10 as you move right of the decimal point.
        </p>
        <p>
            For example, in <m>2.45</m>, the total value is: each digit multiplied by its place value as below
        </p>
    <p>
    <md>
       <mrow> 2.45 \amp= (2 \times 1) + (4 \times 0.1) + (5 \times 0.01)  </mrow>
       <mrow> \amp= 2 + 0.4 + 0.05 </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>
    <p>
    <m>\textbf{Explore}</m>
    </p>
    <sidebyside>
    <p>
    In a school race , Tula run 2.45 kmâ€”that is 2 full kilometers, 400 meters (4 tenths of a km), and 50 meters (5 hundredths of a km). 
    We use total value of digits in a decimal to identify the distance Talu ran that could not form a whole number.
    </p>
